Note: ========================================
Note: GraphQL Translator Tests
Note: ========================================
Note: Comprehensive test suite for GraphQL translation system

Note: Test Coverage:
Note:   - Parser AST construction tests
Note:   - GraphQL->HIR translation tests
Note:   - HIR->GraphQL generation tests
Note:   - Round-trip translation tests
Note: ========================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/graphql/graphql_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/graphql/graphql_to_hir.runa" as ToHIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/graphql/hir_to_graphql.runa" as FromHIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

Note: ========================================
Note: Test Runner
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level driver for the GraphQL translator suite. Runs parser,
to-HIR, from-HIR, and round-trip checks against the real current
translation entry points: parse_graphql (lex+parse from source),
translate_graphql_to_hir (source -> HIR), and generate_graphql
(HIR -> GraphQL text).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Print banner, call each test_* proc serially. Failures reported
inline by assert_* helpers.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All tests print "[OK]" -> clean suite
- Any assert_* failure prints "FAILED:" line -> visible in CI
@End TestCases

Process called "run_all_graphql_tests":
    Note: Run complete GraphQL test suite

    proc print_string with "GraphQL Translator Test Suite"
    proc print_newline

    proc test_parser_query
    proc test_parser_mutation
    proc test_parser_fragments
    proc test_parser_directives
    proc test_graphql_to_hir
    proc test_hir_to_graphql
    proc test_round_trip

    proc print_newline
    proc print_string with "All GraphQL tests completed!"
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Parser Query Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies the GraphQL parser builds an AST for a named query and an
argumented query. parse_graphql lexes and parses the source
internally and returns a non-zero document-node handle on success.
The argumented-query variant verifies the same pipeline survives
variable declarations and field arguments.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two parse+assert blocks:
1. "query GetUser { user { id name } }" -> parse_graphql returns non-zero.
2. "query GetUserById($id: ID!) { user(id: $id) { name } }" ->
   parse_graphql returns non-zero.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "query GetUser { ... }" -> AST handle != 0, passed
- Parser rejects the query -> ast == 0 -> "Query parsed" fails
- "query GetUserById($id: ID!) { user(id: $id) { name } }" -> AST != 0
- Argument parser fails -> ast2 == 0 -> fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_query":
    Note: Test GraphQL query parsing

    proc print_string with "Testing GraphQL query parsing..."
    proc print_newline

    Note: Test simple query
    Let query_source be proc create_string_literal with "query GetUser { user { id name } }"
    Let ast be proc parse_graphql from Parser with query_source

    Let _q_ok be 0
    If ast is not equal to 0:
        Set _q_ok to 1
    End If
    proc assert_true with _q_ok, "Query parsed"

    Note: Test query with arguments
    Let query_args_source be proc create_string_literal with "query GetUserById($id: ID!) { user(id: $id) { name } }"
    Let ast2 be proc parse_graphql from Parser with query_args_source

    Let _qa_ok be 0
    If ast2 is not equal to 0:
        Set _qa_ok to 1
    End If
    proc assert_true with _qa_ok, "Query with args parsed"

    proc print_string with "  Query parsing tests passed"
    proc print_newline
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Parser Mutation Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles mutation operations. A mutation with a
string-literal argument must parse to a non-zero document handle,
proving the parser accepts the mutation keyword and field arguments.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
parse_graphql `mutation CreateUser { createUser(name: "Alice") { id } }`,
assert the returned AST handle is non-zero.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- mutation with string-literal argument -> AST != 0, passed
- Parser rejects mutation -> ast == 0 -> "Mutation parsed" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_mutation":
    Note: Test GraphQL mutation parsing

    proc print_string with "Testing GraphQL mutation parsing..."
    proc print_newline

    Note: Test mutation
    Let mutation_source be proc create_string_literal with "mutation CreateUser { createUser(name: \"Alice\") { id } }"
    Let ast be proc parse_graphql from Parser with mutation_source

    Let _m_ok be 0
    If ast is not equal to 0:
        Set _m_ok to 1
    End If
    proc assert_true with _m_ok, "Mutation parsed"

    proc print_string with "  Mutation parsing tests passed"
    proc print_newline
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Parser Fragment Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles both fragment forms: fragment definition
("fragment UserFields on User { ... }") and fragment spread
("...UserFields" inside a selection set). Both must parse to a
non-zero document handle.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two parse+assert blocks:
1. Fragment definition -> parse_graphql returns non-zero.
2. Query with spread "...UserFields" -> parse_graphql returns non-zero.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "fragment UserFields on User { id name email }" -> AST != 0, passed
- "query { user { ...UserFields } }" -> AST != 0, passed
- Parser fails on "on" keyword -> "Fragment definition parsed" fails
- Parser fails on "..." spread -> "Fragment spread query parsed" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_fragments":
    Note: Test GraphQL fragment parsing

    proc print_string with "Testing GraphQL fragment parsing..."
    proc print_newline

    Note: Test fragment definition
    Let fragment_source be proc create_string_literal with "fragment UserFields on User { id name email }"
    Let ast be proc parse_graphql from Parser with fragment_source

    Let _f_ok be 0
    If ast is not equal to 0:
        Set _f_ok to 1
    End If
    proc assert_true with _f_ok, "Fragment definition parsed"

    Note: Test fragment spread usage
    Let spread_source be proc create_string_literal with "query { user { ...UserFields } }"
    Let ast2 be proc parse_graphql from Parser with spread_source

    Let _fs_ok be 0
    If ast2 is not equal to 0:
        Set _fs_ok to 1
    End If
    proc assert_true with _fs_ok, "Fragment spread query parsed"

    proc print_string with "  Fragment parsing tests passed"
    proc print_newline
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Parser Directive Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles GraphQL field directives (@skip, @include
with arguments). Multiple directives on different fields in the same
selection set exercises the directive list parsing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
parse_graphql a query with @skip(if: true) and @include(if: false)
on two fields. Assert the returned AST handle is non-zero.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Query with two @-directives -> AST != 0, passed
- Parser fails on @ token -> ast == 0 -> "Directive query parsed" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_directives":
    Note: Test GraphQL directive parsing

    proc print_string with "Testing GraphQL directive parsing..."
    proc print_newline

    Note: Test directives on fields
    Let directive_source be proc create_string_literal with "query { user { name @skip(if: true) email @include(if: false) } }"
    Let ast be proc parse_graphql from Parser with directive_source

    Let _d_ok be 0
    If ast is not equal to 0:
        Set _d_ok to 1
    End If
    proc assert_true with _d_ok, "Directive query parsed"

    proc print_string with "  Directive parsing tests passed"
    proc print_newline
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: GraphQL to HIR Translation Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
End-to-end GraphQL source-to-HIR check. translate_graphql_to_hir
lexes, parses, and lowers the source to HIR in one step, returning
a non-zero HIR document handle on success.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. translate_graphql_to_hir("query { user { name } }", 0) -> hir.
2. Assert hir is non-zero.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "query { user { name } }" -> HIR handle != 0, passed
- Translation fails -> hir == 0 -> "GraphQL translated to HIR" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_graphql_to_hir":
    Note: Test GraphQL source to HIR translation

    proc print_string with "Testing GraphQL to HIR translation..."
    proc print_newline

    Note: Test simple query translation
    Let query_source be proc create_string_literal with "query { user { name } }"
    Let hir be proc translate_graphql_to_hir from ToHIR with query_source, 0

    Let _h_ok be 0
    If hir is not equal to 0:
        Set _h_ok to 1
    End If
    proc assert_true with _h_ok, "GraphQL translated to HIR"

    proc print_string with "  GraphQL to HIR translation tests passed"
    proc print_newline
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: HIR to GraphQL Generation Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Reverse direction: translate a query to HIR and emit it back to
GraphQL text with generate_graphql, then assert the output contains
both the "query" keyword and the "user" field name. This exercises
the full HIR->GraphQL emitter on a real HIR built by the frontend.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. translate_graphql_to_hir("query { user }", 0) -> hir.
2. generate_graphql(hir) -> graphql_output.
3. string_contains(graphql_output, "query") AND ditto "user".
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Query HIR -> output contains "query" and "user", passed
- Emitter drops "query" keyword -> "Generated GraphQL contains query" fails
- Emitter drops field name -> "Generated GraphQL contains user" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_hir_to_graphql":
    Note: Test HIR to GraphQL generation

    proc print_string with "Testing HIR to GraphQL generation..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "query { user { name } }"
    Let hir be proc translate_graphql_to_hir from ToHIR with source, 0

    Note: Generate GraphQL
    Let graphql_output be proc generate_graphql from FromHIR with hir

    Note: Check output contains "query"
    Let query_needle be proc create_string_literal with "query"
    Let contains_query be proc string_contains with graphql_output, query_needle
    proc assert_equals with contains_query, 1, "Generated GraphQL contains query"

    Let user_needle be proc create_string_literal with "user"
    Let contains_user be proc string_contains with graphql_output, user_needle
    proc assert_equals with contains_user, 1, "Generated GraphQL contains user"

    proc print_string with "  HIR to GraphQL generation tests passed"
    proc print_newline
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Round-Trip Translation Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Full pipeline check: GraphQL source -> HIR -> GraphQL text. Four
contains-checks ("query", "user", "id", "name") verify the salient
tokens survive both translation directions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. translate_graphql_to_hir("query GetUser { user { id name email } }", 0)
   -> hir.
2. generate_graphql(hir) -> graphql_output.
3. string_contains assertions for "query", "user", "id", "name".
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "query GetUser { user { id name email } }" -> output contains
  query+user+id+name, passed
- Emitter drops operation keyword -> "Round-trip contains query" fails
- Emitter drops field -> "Round-trip contains user/id/name" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_round_trip":
    Note: Test GraphQL -> HIR -> GraphQL round-trip

    proc print_string with "Testing round-trip translation..."
    proc print_newline

    Note: Test simple query round-trip
    Let query_source be proc create_string_literal with "query GetUser { user { id name email } }"
    Let hir be proc translate_graphql_to_hir from ToHIR with query_source, 0

    Note: HIR -> GraphQL
    Let graphql_output be proc generate_graphql from FromHIR with hir

    Note: Check semantic equivalence (contains key elements)
    Let query_needle be proc create_string_literal with "query"
    Let contains_query be proc string_contains with graphql_output, query_needle
    proc assert_equals with contains_query, 1, "Round-trip contains query"

    Let user_needle be proc create_string_literal with "user"
    Let contains_user be proc string_contains with graphql_output, user_needle
    proc assert_equals with contains_user, 1, "Round-trip contains user"

    Let id_needle be proc create_string_literal with "id"
    Let contains_id be proc string_contains with graphql_output, id_needle
    proc assert_equals with contains_id, 1, "Round-trip contains id"

    Let name_needle be proc create_string_literal with "name"
    Let contains_name be proc string_contains with graphql_output, name_needle
    proc assert_equals with contains_name, 1, "Round-trip contains name"

    proc print_string with "  Round-trip translation tests passed"
    proc print_newline
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Helper Functions
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Equality assertion. Failure prints the message plus the expected
and actual operands so a failing test localizes immediately.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If actual != expected, print "FAILED: <message> (expected: E, actual: A)"
+ newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "assert_equals" takes actual as Integer, expected as Integer, message as String:
    Note: Assert two integers are equal

    If actual is not equal to expected:
        proc print_string with "FAILED: "
        proc print_string with message
        proc print_string with " (expected: "
        proc print_integer with expected
        proc print_string with ", actual: "
        proc print_integer with actual
        proc print_string with ")"
        proc print_newline
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Boolean assertion. Failure prints just the message.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If condition != 1, print "FAILED: <message>" + newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "assert_true" takes condition as Integer, message as String:
    Note: Assert condition is true

    If condition is not equal to 1:
        proc print_string with "FAILED: "
        proc print_string with message
        proc print_newline
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Naive substring search used by emitter and round-trip tests to
verify GraphQL keywords survive translation. Operates on the
null-terminated C strings produced by the generator.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Empty needle -> 1. needle longer than haystack -> 0. Slide a window
over haystack; if all needle bytes match at any position -> 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "string_contains" takes haystack as String, needle as String returns Integer:
    Note: Check if haystack contains needle substring

    Let haystack_len be proc string_length from StringCore with haystack
    Let needle_len be proc string_length from StringCore with needle

    If needle_len is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    If needle_len is greater than haystack_len:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    Let max_i be haystack_len minus needle_len

    While i is less than or equal to max_i:
        Let matches be 1
        Let j be 0

        While j is less than needle_len:
            Let h_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with haystack, i plus j
            Let n_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with needle, j

            If h_char is not equal to n_char:
                Set matches to 0
                Break
            End If

            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Thin wrapper around StringCore.create_from_literal so call sites
read as "create_string_literal" without taking a hard dependency on
the exact primitive name.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forward to StringCore.create_from_literal(value).
@End Implementation

Process called "create_string_literal" takes value as String returns Integer:
    Note: Create string from string literal

    Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with value
End Process

Note: print_string, print_newline, and print_integer are bootstrap-runtime
Note: globals; test code calls them directly.
